<section xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:lang="en-US" xml:id="radicals-rational-exponents">
  <title>Rational Exponents</title>

  <p>
    The power to a power rule of exponents relates that <m>(x^m)^n=x^{mn}</m>.  This rule is fairly intuitive when both exponents are positive.  For example, in the expression <m>(x^4)^3</m> there are three factors of <m>x^4</m>, each of which contains four factors of <m>x</m>, so all together there are four factors of <m>x</m>, three times, i.e. <m>3 \cdot 4</m> factor of <m>x</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    While the power to a power rule is less intuitive once you move away from positive integer exponents, the rule remains the same regardless of the nature of the exponents.  For example:
    <md>
      <mrow>(x^{1/3})^3\amp=x^{\frac{1}{3} \cdot 3}</mrow>
      <mrow>\amp=x^{1}</mrow>
      <mrow>\amp=x</mrow>
    </md>
    But we already have a name for the expression that when cubed results in <m>x</m>, and that name is <m>\sqrt[3]{x}</m> (the cube root of <m>x</m>).  So it must be the case that <m>x^{1/3}=\sqrt[3]{x}</m>.  In general, is <m>n</m> is any positive integer, then: <me>x^{1/n}=\sqrt[n]{x}</me> and more generally, <me>x^{m/n}=\sqrt[n]{x^m}</me>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Several examples are shown below.
  </p>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Express <m>y^{7/5}</m> as an equivalent radical expression
      </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
      <p> 
        <me>y^{7/5}=\sqrt[5]{y^7}</me>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Express <m>\sqrt[3]{w^{12}}</m> using an equivalent exponential expression
      </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
      <p> 
        <md>
          <mrow>\sqrt[3]{w^{12}}\amp=w^{12/3}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=w^4</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Express <m>\sqrt{x^9}</m> using an equivalent exponential expression
      </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
      <p> 
        <me>\sqrt{x^9}=x^{9/2}</me>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <p>
    You can use <xref ref="radicals-rational-exponents-geogebra-figure-1">Figure</xref> to explore this definition some more.
  </p>

  <exploration>
    <figure xml:id="radicals-rational-exponents-geogebra-figure-1">
      <caption>
        Explore the Meaning of Rational Exponents.
      </caption>
      <interactive platform="geogebra" width="100%" aspect="9:5">
