  <p>
    As long as both the numerator and denominator of a rational exponent are fairly small positive numbers, it is fairly easy to evaluate expressions that include rational exponents using the rule <m>x^{m/n}=\sqrt[n]{x^m}</m>.
  </p>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Evaluate <m>16^{1/2}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>16^{1/2}\amp=\sqrt{16}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=4</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Evaluate <m>8^{2/3}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>8^{2/3}\amp=\sqrt[3]{8^2}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=\sqrt[3]{64}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=4</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Evaluate <m>100^{3/2}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>100^{3/2}\amp=\sqrt{100^3}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=\sqrt{1000000}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=1000</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <p>
    When the numerator of the rational exponent is large, the rule <m>x^{m/n}=\sqrt[n]{x^m}</m> can become quite cumbersome.  Consider, for example, evaluating <m>9^{5/2}</m>.  If we try to use the standard form we hit a brick wall.  First, it's not trivial to calculate that <m>9^5=59,049</m> (reality check ... I grabbed my calculator).  Now that I have the value of 59,049, I have to determine its square root.  Oh my!
  </p>
  <p>
    Fortunately for us, the application of the exponent and the application of the radical can be done in either order.  That is:
  </p>
  <p>
    <me>a^{m/n}=\sqrt[n]{x^m}   \text{  and  }   a^{m/n}=(\sqrt[n]{x})^m</me>
  </p>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Using the second option, evaluate <m>9^{5/2}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>9^{5/2}\amp=(\sqrt{9})^5</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=3^5</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=243</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Using the second option, evaluate <m>16^{7/4}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>16^{7/4}\amp=(\sqrt[4]{16})^7</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=2^7</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=128</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <p>
    Rational exponents are allowed to be negative.  If that's the case, you probably want to deal with the negative aspect of the exponent before taking on the fractional aspect.
  </p>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Evaluate <m>27^{-2/3}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>27^{-2/3}\amp=\frac{1}{27^{2/3}}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=\frac{1}{(\sqrt[3]{27})^2}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=\frac{1}{3^2}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=\frac{1}{9}</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <p>
    Sometimes radical expressions can be simplified after first rewriting the expressions using rational exponents and applying the appropriate rules of exponents.  If the resultant expression still has a rational exponent, it is standard to convert back to radical notation.  Several examples follow.
  </p>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Use rational exponents to simplify <m></m>.  Where appropriate, your final result should be converted back to radical form.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>\sqrt[3]{y^2} \cdot \sqrt[6]{y}\amp=y^{2/3}y^{1/6}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=y^{2/3+1/6}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=y^{5/6}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=\sqrt[6]{y^5}</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Use rational exponents to simplify <m>\sqrt[8]{t^4}</m>.  Where appropriate, your final result should be converted back to radical form.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>\sqrt[8]{t^4}\amp=t^{4/8}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=t^{1/2}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=\sqrt{t}</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Use rational exponents to simplify <m>\sqrt[10]{\sqrt{5^{40}}}</m>.  Where appropriate, your final result should be converted back to radical form.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>\sqrt[10]{\sqrt{5^{40}}}\amp=\sqrt[10]{5^{40/2}}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=\sqrt[10]{5^{20}}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=5^{20/10}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=5^2</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=25</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <exercises>

    <exercisegroup>

      <introduction>
        <p>
          Convert each exponential expression to a radical expression and each radical expression to an exponential expression.  When converting to a rational exponent, reduce the exponent if possible.  Assume that all variables represent positive values.
        </p>
      </introduction>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>x^{1/3}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>x^{1/3}=\sqrt[3]{x}</m>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>y^{5/4}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>y^{5/4}=\sqrt[4]{y^5}</m>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>z^{2/5}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>z^{2/5}=\sqrt[5]{z^2}</m>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\sqrt[11]{x^5}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>\sqrt[11]{x^5}=x^{5/11}</m>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\sqrt[4]{y^{20}}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>
              \begin{aligned}[t]
              \sqrt[4]{y^{20}}\amp=y^{20/4}\\
              \amp=y^5
              \end{aligned}
            </m> 
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\sqrt[15]{t^3}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>
              \begin{aligned}[t]
              \sqrt[15]{t^3}\amp=t^{3/15}\\
              \amp=t^{1/5}
              \end{aligned}
            </m>   
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Determine the value of each expression.
        </p>
      </introduction>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>4^{1/2}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>
              \begin{aligned}[t]
              4^{1/2}\amp=\sqrt{4}\\
              \amp=2
              \end{aligned}
            </m>  
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>27^{-1/3}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>
              \begin{aligned}[t]
              27^{-1/3}\amp=\frac{1}{27^{1/3}}\\
              \amp=\frac{1}{\sqrt[3]{27}}\\
              \amp=\frac{1}{3}
              \end{aligned}
            </m>  
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\left(\frac{4}{9}\right)^{-1/2}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>
              \begin{aligned}[t]
              \left(\frac{4}{9}\right)^{-1/2}\amp=\left(\frac{9}{4}\right)^{1/2}\\
              \amp=\sqrt{\frac{9}{4}}\\
              \amp=\frac{3}{2}
              \end{aligned}
            </m>    
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>8^{7/3}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>
              \begin{aligned}[t]
              8^{7/3}\amp=(\sqrt[3]{8})^7\\
              \amp=2^7\\
              \amp=128
              \end{aligned}
            </m>    
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>100^{5/2}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>
              \begin{aligned}[t]
              100^{5/2}\amp=(\sqrt{100})^5\\
              \amp=10^5\\
              \amp=100,000
              \end{aligned}
            </m>  
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>16^{-9/4}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>
              \begin{aligned}[t]
              16^{-9/4}\amp=\frac{1}{16^{9/4}}\\
              \amp=\frac{1}{(\sqrt[4]{16})^9}\\
              \amp=\frac{1}{2^9}\\
              \amp=\frac{1}{512}
              \end{aligned}
            </m>    
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Simplify each radical expression after first rewriting the expression in exponential form.  Assume that all variables represent positive values.  Where appropriate, your final result should be converted back to radical form.
        </p>
      </introduction>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\sqrt[5]{t^{20}}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>
              \begin{aligned}[t]
              \sqrt[5]{t^{20}}\amp=t^{20/5}\\
              \amp=t^4
              \end{aligned}
            </m>         
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>6\sqrt[33]{x^{77}}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>
              \begin{aligned}[t]
              6\sqrt[33]{x^{77}}\amp=6x^{77/33}\\
              \amp=6x^{7/3}\\
              \amp=6\sqrt[3]{x^7}
              \end{aligned}
            </m>   
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>(\sqrt{3})^{10}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>
              \begin{aligned}[t]
              (\sqrt{3})^{10}\amp=3^{10/2}\\
              \amp=3^5\\
              \amp=243
              \end{aligned}
            </m>   
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\sqrt[4]{9^2}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>
              \begin{aligned}[t]
              \sqrt[4]{9^2}\amp=9^{2/4}\\
              \amp=9^{1/2}\\
              \amp=\sqrt{9}\\
              \amp=3
              \end{aligned}
            </m>  
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\sqrt{w}\sqrt[4]{w}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>
              \begin{aligned}[t]
              \sqrt{w}\sqrt[4]{w}\amp=w^{1/2}w^{1/4}\\
              \amp=w^{3/4}\\
              \amp=\sqrt[4]{w^3}
              \end{aligned}
            </m> 
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\sqrt[7]{x^6}\sqrt[7]{x}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>
              \begin{aligned}[t]
              \sqrt[7]{x^6}\sqrt[7]{x}\amp=x^{6/7}x^{1/7}\\
              \amp=x^1\\
              \amp=x
              \end{aligned}
            </m>    
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>(\sqrt[12]{x^7y^{16}})^{36}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>
              \begin{aligned}[t]
              (\sqrt[12]{x^7y^{15}})^{36}\amp=(x^7y^{16})^{36/12}\\
              \amp=(x^7y^{16})^3\\
              \amp=x^{21}y^{48}
              \end{aligned}
            </m>     
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\sqrt[5]{\sqrt[3]{x^{15}}}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>
              \begin{aligned}[t]
              \sqrt[15]{\sqrt[3]{x^{15}}}\amp=\sqrt[15]{x^{15/3}}\\
              \amp=\sqrt[15]{x^5}\\
              \amp=x^{5/15}\\
              \amp=x^{1/3}\\
              \amp=\sqrt[3]{x}
              \end{aligned}
            </m>       
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

    </exercisegroup>

  </exercises>

</section>
